name: The COVID Tracking Project

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: More than 800 volunteers performed tens of thousands of hours of work this past year to make our data collection and analysis work possible.   Here’s an in-depth look at how we welcomed, trained, and supported our volunteers.  https://t.co/OJqbJyLZXJ

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: We hope to see better documentation and more states’ submission problems addressed so that state and federal data match better. But we are heartened to see some improvements take hold.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Since we last looked at it in February 2021, the federal government has changed its data sourcing for six jurisdictions and corrected submission problems in three, often improving the data greatly.  https://t.co/kDVbxfNNwB

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Throughout the pandemic, the federal government has struggled to count COVID-19 tests. Its dataset has long shown signs of infrastructural problems:  https://t.co/MGFsc1Ilqw

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: State by state, federal COVID-19 testing data is getting better. Over the last few months, we have observed federal efforts to address many of the dataset’s most pressing problems.  https://t.co/Vd92w6lIqr

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: We’d like to hear from you: How have our data and analysis helped you?  https://t.co/Gz3dIobCU2

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: .@dpatil summed up our impact at an event in March: “You filled a gap that is essential and I fundamentally believe you and the team saved an incredible number of lives.”

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our data has even been cited in 30 pandemic-related lawsuits and legal filings, from voting rights litigation to civil rights lawsuits across the country.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Since the beginning of the pandemic, states and cities used our data in travel advisories and emergency declarations. The Los Angeles City Council passed a resolution to increase production of COVID-19 testing kits that cited our testing data.  https://t.co/nbxylDP0ri

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our work led to more than 30 changes to COVID-19 data points on state websites, from correcting errors to releasing new data. We also pushed for states to report tests in units capturing repeat testing and to report race and ethnicity data, and now, most do.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Congress relied on our data, too: our work was cited in at least 11 letters from lawmakers about the pandemic, and we’re referenced in more than a dozen congressional reports. We were even cited in a bill on COVID-19 data.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our data was used across the federal government: by two presidential administrations, by public health officials including the CDC’s vaccine advisory council, and many federal agencies, from the Department of Energy to the State Department.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Researchers relied on our data to study the pandemic: we’ve been cited in more than 1,000 papers, including medical journals like The New England Journal of Medicine, Nature, JAMA, The Lancet, and Science.  https://t.co/XWJCEgVZUL

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: We became a major data source used by U.S. and international outlets across the political spectrum with more than 7,700 press mentions. We also responded to thousands of media and citizen requests for information on COVID-19 data.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our largely volunteer-run effort became a definitive and trustworthy source for US COVID-19 data and analysis: for media, scientists and medical professionals, academics, and the government.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: For most of the project, we’ve been laser-focused on gathering data. We recently began a process to understand *how* our data has been used. Here’s what we found.  https://t.co/Gz3dIobCU2

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: As researchers with a national lens, we hope this analysis might help policymakers and health officials to identify common problems with gathering the data and target improvements moving forward.  https://t.co/wHdZBrf9ME

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Finally, we look at data presentation. Design decisions affect accessibility, and we’ve seen states require users to navigate pesky buttons and toggles. We’ve also found that states struggle to communicate known backlogs and delays, which might lead to context getting lost.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Next, we look at how states make their data available. Some states report metrics in percentages, without raw numbers. Some provide granular data while others report only summaries. And some states don’t report some metrics at all.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: First up: data definitions. More than one year in, many facets of COVID-19 data are still not standardized. States have defined metrics inconsistently, making summaries and comparisons difficult if not impossible.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: With little guidance from the feds, states have had to make their own decisions about compiling and presenting COVID-19 data, leading to sweeping inconsistencies. Here are some of the key reporting problems we found.  https://t.co/wHdZBrf9ME

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: A special thanks to @NotoriousRSG for her work on these annotations and the data quality team.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: See the full annotations here:  https://t.co/Hk9QWZGPF2

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: We found that states differ in how they track patients with confirmed COVID-19, suspected COVID-19, or both. We also observed some states lumping metrics, making comparisons difficult.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Today we’re releasing research on hospitalization data definitions. Hospitalizations are one of the most critical metrics for understanding the state of the pandemic.  https://t.co/0bRyer4wuz

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Read all our advice from @kissane and @jessicamalaty  here:  https://t.co/DTlE4myX1e

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Tip 6: Be cautious about what the data can say. If you’re trying to extract insights from the data itself, it can be very easy—especially within a headline—to make causal claims when only correlative evidence is available.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Tip 5: Get familiar with caveats. The most recent dates in epidemiological datasets are always incomplete—because, for example, the data points for people who died today won’t finish being reported for many days, weeks, or even months in the future.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Tip 4: Watch out for definitional mismatches and alternate dating schemes. Be aware that different jurisdictions chose different ways of defining and reporting their metrics.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Tip 3: Holiday and weather-related reporting issues happen when national or natural events occur across many states at once, and can mimic shifts in the pandemic. Look for holidays or major disruptions that might have artificially depressed—and then inflated—the data.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Tip 2: Data backlogs—and the “data dumps” that occur when those backlogs are resolved—can mimic major declines and then jumps, especially in cases, tests, and deaths. Look for explanations on state dashboards and call public health officials.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Tip 1: If you see dramatic movement in the data, look for contextual clues before interpreting it as a change in the pandemic. Day-of-week effects in data arranged by date of report produce predictable reporting swings over the course of each week.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: So today, we’re offering a brief cheat sheet on avoiding some of the most common errors we’ve seen.  https://t.co/DTlE4myX1e

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Over the past few weeks, we’ve noticed that newsrooms of all sizes—and even some government agencies—have fallen into some of the data potholes that we’ve become familiar with in our year of wrangling public COVID-19 data.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: To begin to protect our most vulnerable, regulators must  change their approach to the oversight of these facilities—and this oversight must include mandatory data collection, rigorous analysis, and then swift action based on what the data reveals.  https://t.co/CIS1BJqJsV

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Some good news: The vaccines are working. All COVID-19 deaths have been declining for many weeks, but the share of these deaths that are associated with nursing-home outbreaks has declined substantially.  https://t.co/ZhXZJKz3Uz

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Because of data and reporting issues, these figures are known undercounts. The true toll of the pandemic among  workers and residents in long-term-care facilities is higher than these figures can show.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: We estimate that as of March 2021, about 8 percent of people who live in US long-term-care facilities have died of COVID-19: Nearly one in 12.  https://t.co/CIS1BJ984l

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Based on official state figures compiled by our team, as of March 4, 2021, at least 174,474 people had died of COVID-19 in long-term-care facilities. This represents 34% of the total deaths due to COVID-19 in the US.  https://t.co/0yYIP5y2jm

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Over the past 10 months, we've tried to determine how COVID-19 affected some of the people most vulnerable to the virus: residents of long-term-care facilities.  https://t.co/CIS1BJqJsV

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Finally, we’ve outlined the various federal datasets for people people who want the simplest possible way to track the COVID-19 pandemic in the US.   https://t.co/quJMBxIjod

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Further analysis of the federal COVID-19 race and ethnicity datasets, in comparison to the data we collected from states and territories, is forthcoming.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: The data we have collected from states and territories has always been incomplete and shown inequities in who is being affected by the pandemic and to what degree. Both of these characteristics are also true of the currently available federal COVID-19 data on race and ethnicity.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: The federal data can be better, by collecting and publishing race and ethnicity data more consistently and comprehensively, presenting the data in clear, accessible ways, and being transparent about data sources and contexts.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Federal race and ethnicity COVID-19 data is not comprehensive enough to represent people’s experience of the pandemic in the United States. Most data is only available nationally, not by state.  https://t.co/H4eLwAXYA3

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our Federal Data 101 about race and ethnicity data is published.  Publicly available federal race and ethnicity COVID-19 data is currently usable and improving, although it shares many of the problems we’ve found in state-reported  data.   https://t.co/G4BKjuWord

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: We don't know what path this Michigan outbreak is going to take, but this could prove a bellwether for what happens when new variants of concern encounter populations with less vaccine access.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: The other big question is what role variants of concern are playing in Michigan. Our genomic surveillance remains limited, but the CDC reports that Michigan has the second-most confirmed cases of the B.1.1.7 variant, after Florida.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Two important pieces of context: Statewide, just 28% of Black residents 65+ are known to have received a first dose of vaccine. Though that data is incomplete, CDC numbers show that 66% of the U.S. population aged 65+ has received at least one dose of vaccine.  https://t.co/58GLniDZjK

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: There had been some hopes that if we did see cases rise somewhere, hospitalizations would not follow because many vulnerable people have been vaccinated. But Michigan hospitalizations have increased 45% from their February low.   https://t.co/hKVU7o4eJV

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: For many weeks now, the number of cases and hospitalizations has been going down across the country. Unfortunately, that trend has now reversed in the state of Michigan. Cases * and * hospitalizations are both on the rise there.  https://t.co/RTR6LxKveA

tweet: And—this is @alexismadrigal and @kissane—we have to thank CTP’s contributors. This project came out of nothing. You became its blood and bones. We know how much you sacrificed—jobs, school, kidtime—and how much it sometimes hurt to handle the numbers that defined this year.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: In the beginning of the pandemic, @edyong209 told us that natural disasters bring people together, but pandemics tear people apart. We like to think that CTP was an active protest against those divisions.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our project's key value is a culture of gratitude, saying thank you even for things that are a normal part of the job. In this year where so much has come at all of us, it has helped to remember that at the very least, we have each other to be thankful for.  https://t.co/DRhDeEow11

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Second, thank you to the health department officials who gathered up the data that we compile. We know that we are merely the last step that this data takes. What you all have done, despite funding cuts and impossible hours, is the definition of public service.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: We have many thank yous. First, to the frontline healthcare workers, who risked their lives to treat this emerging disease.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our data collection ends today, but the CTP will continue publishing accountability work. We want to use our knowledge of the nation's data to show how we might fix the structural problems we've identified.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: It's impossible to take in the sweep of the pandemic. But on this day last year, fewer than 20 people were known to have died from COVID-19 in the US. There were only 574 cases. Now, 10 states have seen more than 1 in 500 of their residents killed during the pandemic.  https://t.co/8kYBDdt1ty

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Deaths have tracked the other metrics, at a delay, as they have through the pandemic. This is the first day we've seen fewer than 1000 deaths reported since November 29, more than 3 months ago.  https://t.co/otU5rlYfLe

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Hospitalizations have also fallen from highs over 130 thousand down to just over 40 thousand today.  https://t.co/w1odHP3fPU

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: We ended up tracking other metrics. Cases reached heights we never could have imagined in the early days. The 7-day average got to 250 thousand cases per day in early January. Today, states reported the fewest number of cases since October 6, before the winter surge.  https://t.co/T8W8RK5e0y

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: The project was initially created to track testing. The first few days, states reported just a few thousand total tests. Today, states reported 1.2 million tests. The single-day high for the year was December 5 at 2.3 million. Cumulatively, we've tracked 363 million tests.  https://t.co/Doh6Rdpk1p

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our daily update is published. States reported 1.2 million tests, 41k cases, 40,212 hospitalized COVID-19 patients, and 839 deaths. This is our final day of data collection after a very long year.  https://t.co/fKDkp3iL03

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: The number of people in the hospital with COVID-19 continues to decline in every US region. The Midwest and West are now both under 100 COVID-19 hospitalizations per million people.  https://t.co/ZVtgBarFWe

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: A Sunday-to-Saturday view of the data makes the storm-related reporting dip and rise of the previous two weeks of test, case, and death data particularly clear. More about that in our final weekly update:  https://t.co/WR78xKUHiN  https://t.co/7zAAYSVSZK

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Our daily update is published. States reported 1.4M COVID-19 tests, 60k cases, 41,401 people currently hospitalized, and 1,674 deaths.  https://t.co/4dicgp6Pm4

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: More broadly, we are so grateful to the health officials who have worked inhuman hours for more than a year to collect and publish the best data they could, despite our nation’s rickety public health infrastructure—and who will keep publishing it for the foreseeable future.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: In all, we managed to switch 45 of 56 US jurisdictions to explicit totals in totalTestResults. And 54 jurisdictions now post at least current (if not historical) data in units of tests. We are grateful to the efforts of state health officials who made these improvements possible.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Switching each state’s totalTestResults from calculated to explicit numbers required getting complete historical testing data from states. We tried to get the data in units of tests—not people—because counting tests better captures testing volume.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: These changes close the book on work we began in August 2020 to improve the data in totalTestResults. When our project began, most states shared positive and negative results only, so we summed those figures to calculate totals for every state.   https://t.co/8PAprv4aoU

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: In the last of our rolling updates to our totalTestResults API field before we end data collection tomorrow, we switched totalTestResults for MT, NM, and WV from summing positive+negative to drawing data directly from totalTestsViral.   https://t.co/9xPNckVjIM

name: The COVID Tracking Project

name: The COVID Tracking Project

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: As you use or build on our work, keep in mind the annotations aren’t perfect. But we decided that providing a comprehensive look at our annotations was more important than releasing only a subset of the information after we’d polished it. Find them here:  https://t.co/Hk9QWZGPF2

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Tracking state definitions has been vital to interpreting the data they publish. We hope that this full view of our annotations will be of use to researchers and data users aiming to understand state-level COVID-19 data and the methodologies we’ve used to collect and analyze it.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Definitions are often relegated to small footnotes on state dashboards. But they make a big difference in the data: They can tip the scale between labeling a COVID-19 case as active versus recovered, or between counting or not counting some COVID-19 cases and deaths at all.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: Health data pipelines in the US are siloed, with each state running its own pipelines to collect data on COVID-19’s spread. In the absence of federal guidelines, and constrained by technical limitations of their systems, many of them use different data definitions.

name: The COVID Tracking Project
tweet: The COVID Tracking Project is ending data collection this Sunday. As part of our wind down process, we are for the first time publishing our full data annotations, a set of structured metadata on how states define their COVID-19 metrics.  https://t.co/7ZrFAIzBre
